{{short description|In astronomy, the measured mass of a planet}} {{mergeto|Minimum mass|discuss=Talk:Minimum mass#Proposed merger of True mass|date=January 2018}} The term '''''true mass''''' is synonymous with the term [[mass]], but is used in [[astronomy]] to differentiate the measured mass of a planet from the [[minimum mass|lower limit of mass]] usually obtained from [[radial velocity]] techniques.<ref name="ut" /> Methods used to determine the true mass of a [[planet]] include measuring the distance and period of one of its [[natural satellite|satellites]],<ref name="Brown Schaller 2007" /> advanced [[astrometry]] techniques that use the motions of other planets in the same [[star system]],<ref name="ut" /> combining radial velocity techniques with [[Astronomical transit|transit]] observations (which indicate very low orbital inclinations),<ref name="cornell" /> and combining radial velocity techniques with [[parallax|stellar parallax]] measurements (which also determine orbital inclinations).<ref name="Han Black Gatewood 2001" />
