The '''Uhlenhuth Research Laboratory of the University of Freiburg''', originally known as the '''State Research Laboratory''' ({{lang-de|Staatliches Forschungslaboratorium}}), was a [[research institute]] in the field of [[medical microbiology]] and [[infectious diseases]] in [[Freiburg]], [[Germany]]. It was established in 1936 with funding from the [[Notgemeinschaft der Deutschen Wissenschaft|German Research Council]] for the world-renowned microbiologist and immunologist [[Paul Uhlenhuth]] to provide a platform for his continued research after he had retired from his university [[chair (academic)|chair]] at the [[University of Freiburg]], and Uhlenhuth served as the institute's director until his death in 1957 at the age of 87. The scientific staff consisted of Uhlenhuth and a small number of researchers. As the name suggests, it was a [[states of Germany|state]] institute in the [[Republic of Baden]] and later in [[Baden-Württemberg]]. It was originally an independent research institution, albeit closely associated with the University of Freiburg, but in the early 1950s, the institute formally became part of the Faculty of Medicine at the University of Freiburg. After Uhlenhuth's death, it was integrated in the Institute of Medical Microbiology and Hygiene.

The institute was located in Hebelstraße 42 in central Freiburg, in the same building as the university's Institute of Medical Microbiology and Hygiene, and within the central university campus area.<ref>[http://dl.ub.uni-freiburg.de/diglit/vvuf_1956_ss/0068/ocr?sid=c6a767a379e79a3f44c01cb6920108f3 Personen- und Vorlesungsverzeichnis : Albert-Ludwigs-Universität Freiburg im Breisgau], 1956</ref><ref>Eduard Seidler, ''Die Medizinische Fakultät der Albert-Ludwigs-Universität Freiburg im Breisgau: Grundlagen und Entwicklungen'', Springer-Verlag, 2013, p. 268</ref>

